STATEMENT
OF
PURPOSE

Last
year,
The
Brown
Daily
Herald
released
a
special
issue
devoted

to
exploring
the
New
Curriculum
and
the
challenges
which
go
with

it.
The
special
issue
which
you
are
reading
could
be
said
to
deal
with

the
execution
of
that
curriculum,
by
exploring
the
practices
of
those

who
work
with
the
students,
the
teachers,
and
how
the
administration

encourages
and
discourages
the
work
of
learning.

The
feature
articles
in
this
issue
attempt
to
take
critical
eyes
to

what
Brown
does
to
encourage â€”and
discourage
a
high
quality

of
teaching.
Does
the
University
only
pay
lip
service
to
teaching,

and
then,
once
the
award
ceremonies
are
over,
ignore
teaching
in

the
tenure
process?
Are
undergraduates
being
shortchanged
by
an

increasing
overreliance
on
teaching
assistants
even
being
used

as
guinea-pigs
for
the
graduate
students'
training?
What
kind
of

resources
is
the
University
providing
to
train
its
younger
professors

and
graduate
students,
and
keep
its
veteran
professors
from
getting

rusty
in
their
skills?
And
when
good
teaching
itself
is
difficult
to

define
and
even
more
difficult
to
institutionalize,
what
can
a
new

Dean
of
the
College
do
to
improve
teaching?

This
issue
also
features
thirteen
profiles
of
professors
saluted
by

their
students
for
making
unique
efforts
in
their
work
with
students.

It
is
hoped
that
these
conversations,
as
we've
called
them,
can
create

discussion
on
what
teaching
is,
what
it
should
be,
and
how
it
can
be

even
better.
For
the
worst
mistake
this
campus
can
make
is
to
spend

too
much
time
patting
itself
on
the
back,
and
too
little
time
striving

to
improve
even
more.
There
may
be
few
easy
answers
as
to
what

makes
a
great
teacher,
a
poor
teacher,
and
how
a
university
can

sponsor
and
improve
its
teaching.
But
engaging
in
a
discussion
of

these
questions
may
be
a
step
in
the
right
direction.
